WEBVTT

00:01.538 --> 00:03.240
Hello family, Tyler here.

00:03.300 --> 00:13.695
I wanted to take a moment to invite you to Bridgetown's 8th Annual Holy Spirit Conference, January 23rd and 24th at Portland's, Colorado.

00:14.376 --> 00:18.602
The theme of this year's conference is going to be the healing after the healing.

00:19.143 --> 00:27.154
We'll be exploring how the miraculous work of the Holy Spirit is often just the first step to the deeper, slower soul level healing.

00:27.682 --> 00:36.012
Like the man-born blind in John 9, each part of us God heals only exposes a deeper part of us awaiting healing from the same God.

00:36.372 --> 00:39.716
And the deepest healing is often the slowest kind.

00:40.557 --> 00:48.547
We're so excited to be joined by contributors like Ruth Haley Barton, Kurt Thompson, Ken Shigamatsu, and Brooke Ligertwood.

00:49.007 --> 00:52.591
Tickets are available now at bridgetown.church.com.

00:52.832 --> 00:54.834
I hope you can join us.

01:08.930 --> 01:20.242
Devote yourselves to prayer, being watchful and thankful, and pray for us too that God may open a door for our message so that we may proclaim the mystery of Christ for which I am in chains.

01:20.983 --> 01:24.006
Pray that I'm a proclaim it clearly as I should.

01:24.066 --> 01:26.769
Be wise in the way you act towards outsiders.

01:27.090 --> 01:28.831
Make the most of every opportunity.

01:29.372 --> 01:35.358
Let your conversation be always full of grace, seasoned with salt, so that you may know how to answer everyone.

01:36.079 --> 01:36.920
This is the word of the Lord.

01:37.981 --> 01:38.642
Thanks be to God.

01:42.178 --> 01:49.086
I have always done my clearest thinking first thing in the morning and always done my most honest praying while walking.

01:49.447 --> 01:57.056
So in my 12 years in New York City, I walked pretty much the same lap around my neighborhood and prayer every single morning.

01:58.117 --> 02:08.149
It was early enough there would still be dark out and so I was almost always nearly the only one on the typically crowded sidewalks with one consistent exception.

02:08.269 --> 02:09.010
There was this

02:09.314 --> 02:37.106
One bar in my neighborhood that stayed open later than everywhere else and it was one of those kind of rough around the edges joints that always smells like stale beer and cheap burgers and there was a same woman who would always be wiping down the counters of this place at around five in the morning when I walked by and the same man who would always be hosing off the sidewalks out front and so I would always cross the street to avoid the splatter and I would carry on in my

02:37.346 --> 02:49.402
prayerful plea for today's work agenda or a need that existed in my home or adoration at the God who set the stars in the sky that I could faintly see on the clearest of mornings.

02:50.043 --> 02:58.214
That was our routine, the four of us, the praying pastor, the immigrant couple, and the God who spoke every last one of us into being.

02:59.095 --> 03:07.186
And then one day it finally occurred to me that maybe these two weren't an interruption to my prayers, but the very center of them.

03:07.970 --> 03:28.306
And that morning I stopped and I watched and I thought about their lives, about the hour plus subway commute they undoubtedly took to arrive at that place every morning and about the life they must have had in their country of origin, about how difficult that life must have been to make the one they were living preferable.

03:28.930 --> 03:48.690
and not just preferable, but valuable, so valuable that they would leave family and comfort to navigate systems and languages and do all of it just to lay claim of a life of cleaning up spilled alcohol and cigarette butts from those who have everything in common with them, save the geographical lottery of their origin point.

03:49.794 --> 04:19.762
And I thought about the God that I was praying to, about a God whose developmental years were spent navigating the systems and languages of an immigrant who had fled circumstances in Israel so bad that Egypt was preferable, even valuable, a God who spent more time as a blue-collar grunt worker than he did as a teacher and a miracle worker, and a God who had decided preference for the company of folks like these that I had crossed the street to maintain a distance from.

04:21.186 --> 04:33.644
And on this particular morning, I noticed the dignity with which they worked, how she wiped down the counter, humming and delighting, charging her rag and mop with the very image of the God that I prayed to.

04:33.684 --> 04:45.842
And the way he looked up at me and smiled, welcoming me, a stranger, like a friend, filling our language-restricted interaction with the image of the God that I prayed to, these two,

04:46.178 --> 04:52.285
If only I had eyes to see were not an interruption to my prayers, but an invitation to deepen them.

04:53.607 --> 05:01.816
And it all prompted a question for me, one I've never been able to shake, one I hope I never do shake, a question that goes something like this.

05:01.936 --> 05:06.842
How do I pull my prayers down from the majesty of the stars above to the sidewalk below?

05:08.024 --> 05:10.066
How do I pray in such a way that

05:10.210 --> 05:16.840
doesn't escape the mess for a brief enlightened moment at dawn, but welcomes God into the mess of the day that I'm just beginning.

05:18.222 --> 05:25.253
That same question came rushing back to me again here in Portland on the first day of school in our second year in the city.

05:25.313 --> 05:31.102
I was dropping Hank off for his first day of second grade and Simon for his first day of kindergarten.

05:31.142 --> 05:36.530
We were that unbearable family taking pictures together in front of the classroom door.

05:37.090 --> 05:58.081
I was already in a rush to take off as soon as the school bell rang, because I had a full day with a packed agenda, but I noticed Kirsten calling every other parent by name and asking about their summer travels and checking in on their siblings and so on, and I was confronted by the tragic irony of it all.

05:59.162 --> 06:06.994
That I spent an hour in prayer every morning walking and talking to God in a wonder-struck eloquent

06:07.970 --> 06:11.956
dialogue on the sidewalks of Portland.

06:12.757 --> 06:16.902
But Kirsten, I'm watching as she's living the prayers that I'm praying.

06:18.264 --> 06:25.795
And so again, I pray, oh gracious God, would you give me more than prayerful words, but would you give me a prayer shaped life?

06:26.696 --> 06:36.850
Would you bring my prayers down from the stars they gaze upon to the ground that I stand on and to the mess down here into my parenting and my husbanding and my befriending and my living and my relating?

06:36.962 --> 06:46.052
You see, the fruit of prayer, and this might surprise you at first, but the fruit of prayer isn't only about miraculous intervention and divine action.

06:46.092 --> 06:56.023
Even more than that, the fruit of prayer is about what happens within the praying person over time after all of our amends.

06:56.764 --> 07:05.394
The real fruit of prayer is the way that it reforms the praying person to see their ordinary world through the eyes of Jesus and then respond in kind.

07:05.506 --> 07:13.976
Praying is an exercise training me to drag the majesty of heaven down onto Brooklyn sidewalks and into Portland school yards.

07:14.477 --> 07:20.745
If you will let him, Jesus will bring prayer closer than you were ready for when you started praying.

07:21.626 --> 07:34.962
Closer than just the power to change the world around you through your secret whispers, but close enough to change the world within you through those secret whispers so that the world around you follows suit behind your prayer shaped life.

07:36.066 --> 07:52.643
I guess what I'm trying to get at here is that as you grow up in the life of prayer, you will become less enamored by what happens between all your dear gods and amens, and a lot more attentive to who you are becoming in your ordinary life after all of your amens.

07:53.886 --> 07:55.570
Devote yourselves to prayer.

07:55.938 --> 08:05.394
counseled the Apostle Paul to the Colossian community of Jesus' apprentices with some final words in the letter about prioritizing the spiritual practice of prayer.

08:05.874 --> 08:14.569
But in the very same breath, he quickly gets to verse five, be wise in the way you act toward outsiders, making the most of every opportunity.

08:14.649 --> 08:20.318
Let your conversation be always full of grace seasoned with salt so that you may know how to answer everyone.

08:20.879 --> 08:22.482
So Paul seems to assume

08:22.722 --> 08:30.598
that the conversation that we begin with God in secret quickly becomes the actions and the conversations that we pick up with our neighbors in public.

08:31.320 --> 08:44.146
Paul, the very guy who said pray without ceasing, seems to imagine a life of undending prayer, not as one where the dialogue of prayer never stops, but one where the life of prayer never stops.

08:44.450 --> 08:45.932
Devote yourselves to prayer.

08:46.012 --> 08:47.494
That's where it all begins, though.

08:47.514 --> 08:53.381
It is the source and the origin point of daily bread and kingdom come alike.

08:54.022 --> 08:58.487
In this English word, devote, it is the Greek term, proskaterreo.

08:58.607 --> 09:04.895
It's a word that is used 10 times in the Bible, almost always in reference to prayer.

09:05.736 --> 09:10.642
Acts chapter 1, they all joined together or devoted themselves constantly in prayer.

09:10.978 --> 09:17.607
Acts two, they devoted themselves to the apostles' teaching and to fellowship to the breaking of bread and to prayer.

09:18.368 --> 09:28.961
Acts six, we will turn this responsibility over to them and we will give our attention or our devotion, our proschetario to prayer.

09:29.422 --> 09:35.730
Romans chapter 12, be joyful and hope, patient and affliction, faithful or devoted in

09:35.842 --> 09:36.283
prayer.

09:36.323 --> 10:00.196
We get an even more fully formed understanding, though, of what this word devoted really means by its alternative uses, by the few times in Scripture that it's used in reference to something other than prayer, like in Acts 10, which speaks of a devout soldier who was one of Cornelius' attendants, and in Romans 13, which speaks of civil servants devoting their time to governing.

10:00.897 --> 10:04.882
So the Bible uses this word, Proskia Terreo, to refer

10:05.026 --> 10:27.581
to the secular vocation of those outside of the church, but then repurposes a vocational word and applies it to all followers of Jesus, naming prayer as your and my primary vocation, the ends to which the bulk of our time, energy, and attention should be given, the center that our lives orbit around.

10:28.001 --> 10:31.026
You see, in the life of the disciple, there are many good things.

10:31.746 --> 10:37.475
work and obligations, appointments, and needs, friends, and neighbors, but there's only one devotion.

10:38.677 --> 10:47.070
There's just one center around which everything else revolves, finding its proper place and the work and the order that sustains and gives life.

10:47.951 --> 10:48.712
And that's prayer.

10:49.894 --> 10:53.660
In your life, you can have many priorities, but you only get one devotion.

10:54.942 --> 10:57.786
And Jesus himself said, no one can serve two masters.

10:58.026 --> 11:00.370
You go, hate the one and love the other or you'll be

11:01.026 --> 11:04.210
devoted to the one and despised the other.

11:04.611 --> 11:13.543
In context, of course, Jesus is speaking about the competing allegiance of Mammon, but the principle here holds for any alternative devotion.

11:14.064 --> 11:26.962
So if all of this is biblically speaking, a vocational concept about the primary devotion of my time, energy, and attention, then it's worth asking, if someone observed me inside and out for a week,

11:27.938 --> 11:42.962
If they heard every thought that passed through my mind and observed every minute of every one of my days, if they watched my habits and practices and priorities objectively, who or what would they say that I am devoted to?

11:44.674 --> 11:47.880
Like what priority do I find a way to uphold no matter what?

11:48.020 --> 11:52.869
What do I manage to purchase when my paychecks are fat and when they're thin?

11:52.949 --> 11:55.714
What do I always live with but never without?

11:56.155 --> 12:03.529
When life goes as planned and gets interrupted when I'm doing well and just barely getting by, what do I always seem to get in?

12:04.110 --> 12:08.658
Who or what am I devoted to?

12:16.898 --> 12:18.760
Am I devoted to my ambition?

12:20.463 --> 12:23.907
Like how much of my mental energy goes toward my career pursuits?

12:23.987 --> 12:27.772
How preoccupied am I by my boss or coworkers opinions?

12:27.812 --> 12:31.057
How closely do I watch my inbox after turning in a project?

12:31.397 --> 12:37.004
How inflated am I by a positive remark and how anxious by a critical one?

12:37.024 --> 12:38.927
How badly do I need to succeed?

12:39.007 --> 12:40.829
How much does it scare me not to?

12:41.210 --> 12:44.434
And who gave me the definition of success that I carry around?

12:46.850 --> 12:48.973
Am I devoted to my social circle?

12:50.495 --> 12:57.946
How much emotional energy do I expend people pleasing at work or peacemaking in my family or competing, criticizing, gossiping and one-upping?

12:59.609 --> 13:04.196
Am I the one who shows up to every happy hour and says yes to every invitation?

13:04.236 --> 13:07.701
Do I spend more time on my social media profile than my soul?

13:08.142 --> 13:13.810
Do I share a million conversations with others but barely whisper a word to the one who spoke me into being?

13:16.706 --> 13:18.208
Am I devoted to my body?

13:18.248 --> 13:33.152
How much of my mind's attention is spent on my diet, my planning, and my calorie counting about what I'll eat today or how what I will eat today will make up for the indulgence that I gave myself into last night?

13:34.313 --> 13:42.106
How much of my time is given to exercise, to the perfecting of my body, to the pursuit of my goal weight, or my ideal figure?

13:42.526 --> 13:45.010
How much regard do I give my physical appearance?

13:45.314 --> 13:55.289
What story do my finances tell me about how much I value maintaining the youth of my complexion or the fashion of my wardrobe or the tone of my skin?

13:58.153 --> 13:59.375
Am I devoted to pleasure?

14:00.677 --> 14:03.100
How much of the work week do I spend planning the weekend?

14:03.821 --> 14:06.706
And how satisfied am I with having nothing going on?

14:06.726 --> 14:08.448
Or how often do I find myself there?

14:08.749 --> 14:11.192
What do I use as a means for escape?

14:11.332 --> 14:12.434
Food, drink?

14:12.578 --> 14:15.202
screens, shopping, activity, people.

14:17.545 --> 14:24.875
Look, there's plenty of reasons to be devoted to prayer, but the first and most obvious one is just this, that any other devotion makes you less.

14:26.117 --> 14:27.539
Only prayer makes you more.

14:28.681 --> 14:32.626
Devote yourself to your ambition and you will climb the corporate ladder until you fall.

14:33.154 --> 14:44.250
And it'll hurt, but you'll get up and you'll keep on climbing and climbing until you've passed your whole life on a ladder that you never got to the top of and forgot why you needed to reach the top rung so badly anyway.

14:45.452 --> 15:03.058
Or maybe worse, you will actually get to the top and then you'll spend more energy fighting off other people who are climbing up to take your spot than you ever did getting there until one day, like a toddler, you're told it's time to let someone else have a turn and then you'll are you and Pat because no one seems to remember or care how long you spent at the top.

15:04.354 --> 15:10.862
Devote yourself to a social circle and you'll feel every minute, every thought you will expend every ounce of energy keeping people happy.

15:11.423 --> 15:14.567
People whose happiness is a riddle, they haven't solved themselves.

15:14.607 --> 15:16.149
So how possibly could you?

15:16.209 --> 15:27.384
You will keep plenty of people happy by hiding your true self for so long that you'll lose track of who you are and what you want and what makes you happy and you'll never draw forth the real them either.

15:27.424 --> 15:32.370
Devote yourself to your body and you will never feel beautiful enough.

15:33.314 --> 15:35.156
You will always be working on yourself.

15:35.216 --> 15:42.084
You will turn everyone else you see into a comparison, making certain that neither you nor the other will ever be enough.

15:42.945 --> 15:45.748
Neither of you seem to the eyes of the one who fashioned you both.

15:45.888 --> 15:48.951
Neither of you honored for the eternity that lives within you both.

15:49.932 --> 16:02.546
Devote yourself to pleasure to your choice means of escape, and you will escape your life's responsibilities with increasing frequency and for longer and longer stretches until you wake up one day to realize you've evacuated altogether.

16:03.362 --> 16:10.113
that you had just one shot at being a mom or dad or son or daughter or friend or lover or disciple.

16:11.095 --> 16:18.487
And you traded it for being the life of your preferred party, a party that everyone else left without you noticing.

16:18.548 --> 16:20.691
Now here you are, turning the lights out alone.

16:22.013 --> 16:27.122
Devote yourself to prayer though, and everything else in your life will fall into proper order.

16:27.490 --> 16:41.428
It will find alignment, and you will not be the center of the story you're living, but rather you will find yourself revolving around a center where life is maintained and sustained through changing seasons and passing years.

16:42.008 --> 16:44.692
Who or what am I devoted to?

16:44.732 --> 16:48.937
I'm not aspirationally, but honestly.

16:50.499 --> 16:54.284
What is my life, my time, my thoughts, my energy, my finances?

16:54.324 --> 16:55.986
What is it all orbit around?

16:58.466 --> 17:05.814
It was a couple years ago when I was confronted by this very question and by the realization that I really wanted my answer to be prayer.

17:06.697 --> 17:08.946
And there was a time when it was, but then

17:09.506 --> 17:22.144
For me, somewhere along the way, in all the coming and going, pastoring and riding, errands and tasks, somewhere in the shuffle of it all, I lost sight of the center around which everything else orbits to sustain life.

17:22.545 --> 17:29.855
Lesser loves have a way of doing this, of kind of slowly, subtly nudging their way into the seat of your life's devotion.

17:31.557 --> 17:33.400
Who or what am I devoted to?

17:35.483 --> 17:37.586
And whenever you can be honest enough,

17:38.082 --> 17:39.944
with yourself to answer that question.

17:39.984 --> 17:43.067
Here's a couple that should follow very closely on its heels.

17:44.809 --> 17:47.192
Do I want to become who it's making me?

17:49.254 --> 17:51.617
And do I get to keep what it's giving me?

17:54.240 --> 17:55.321
Who am I devoted to?

17:55.381 --> 17:59.706
And do I actually want to become what it's making me?

18:01.848 --> 18:07.314
And even if I do, do I get to keep in this life and into the next?

18:08.546 --> 18:09.468
whatever it's given.

18:09.508 --> 18:15.199
My humble conviction is that I want to be devoted to prayer.

18:16.701 --> 18:31.890
And my honest discovery is that a life of prayer is lived on three mountains, Mount Tabor, the Mount of Olives, and Golgotha, a brief, closer look at each.

18:32.738 --> 18:47.037
Let's begin with Mount Tabor, because before that became a mountain in East Portland where you walked off your annual Thanksgiving feast, it was first the mountain that Jesus climbs with Peter, James, and John, leaving the other nine disciples waiting at the bottom.

18:47.658 --> 18:53.526
It's on this mountain that Jesus was transfigured, glowing with the beaming image of God's glory.

18:54.067 --> 19:02.578
Matthew 17, a bright cloud covered them, and a voice from the cloud said, this is my son, whom I love, with him I am well pleased.

19:02.690 --> 19:04.532
listen to him.

19:04.552 --> 19:10.338
Now this is one of three distinct accounts where the Father spoke audibly over the life of the Son.

19:10.958 --> 19:24.892
There's the transfiguration, what we just read, and before this there was Jesus' baptism, and shortly after it, the Father's voice is heard in the temple during Jesus' final week, and the three messages from the Father are nearly identical.

19:25.633 --> 19:30.578
At His baptism we hear, you are my Son, whom I love, with you I am well pleased.

19:31.042 --> 19:36.672
And then a glow on table we hear, this is my son, whom I love, with him I am well pleased.

19:37.093 --> 19:41.160
At the temple during Jesus' final week, he cries, Father, glorify your name.

19:41.180 --> 19:45.528
And then a voice comes from heaven saying, I have glorified it and we'll glorify it again.

19:45.548 --> 19:49.395
In context, it's, you're already bringing me glory, son.

19:50.437 --> 19:55.346
Not in some future aspiration of who you might become, but in who you are today.

19:56.098 --> 20:03.347
Surely the three occasions where we eavesdrop in on Trinitarian dialogue are some of the standout moments in Scripture, right?

20:05.049 --> 20:18.626
I mean, you would think God would have used the opportunity to say something a bit more productive, like to rebuke the corrupt priests or the Roman oppressors or to call Israel to repentance or to explain the meaning of life once and for all.

20:19.787 --> 20:25.394
But when God spoke loud enough for His Son and the whole world to hear, He only ever had one message.

20:26.754 --> 20:29.279
I love you and I'm proud of you.

20:31.304 --> 20:36.415
There is no discovery that you will ever make more formative than the revelation of the Father's love for you.

20:37.497 --> 20:40.263
And the Father's love cannot be learned, only discovered.

20:41.446 --> 20:47.218
If we are to know the Father's love, it's going to take something more than a solid theological library and sound doctrine.

20:47.810 --> 21:00.250
We can get belief through knowledge shared with us by others, but knowing like the relational and experiential variety, that requires that I believe objectively and also experience subjectively.

21:01.211 --> 21:12.850
And as long as we're talking about textbooks and math problems, objective information is going to do just fine, but the second we switch to something like relationship, then the subjective becomes essential.

21:13.698 --> 21:18.584
Subjectivity gets a really bad rap in a culture like ours that's obsessed with the cognitive.

21:18.944 --> 21:23.669
But love between two people is the most universally pursued human experience.

21:23.950 --> 21:25.832
It is the core plot to every film.

21:26.212 --> 21:28.855
It is the chorus of every song in the top 40.

21:29.196 --> 21:30.657
And love cannot be learned.

21:31.859 --> 21:32.679
Only discovered.

21:33.841 --> 21:37.385
So here are the father's affirmation over you.

21:38.166 --> 21:39.607
You are my daughter.

21:40.608 --> 21:41.970
You are my son.

21:42.946 --> 21:43.967
whom I love.

21:45.069 --> 21:48.994
With you, I am well pleased."

21:50.916 --> 21:58.445
Now that's not all prayer is, but it is the only foundation upon which to build a life of prayer.

21:59.346 --> 22:03.291
You cannot sustain a life of prayer by believing in the power of prayer.

22:04.533 --> 22:08.658
You sustain a life of prayer by believing I am the beloved of God.

22:09.730 --> 22:11.800
He is my son and my shield.

22:11.820 --> 22:14.191
He is the warmth on my face on life's best days.

22:14.211 --> 22:16.562
And he is the shelter in the storm on life's worst.

22:16.930 --> 22:22.299
He is the one who trains my hands for battle and he is the one who binds up my wounds when I come home injured.

22:22.800 --> 22:32.576
I'm not advocating for prayer today because I'm super into the spiritual practice of prayer or even because I'm really convinced about the power of prayer.

22:32.956 --> 22:41.530
I believe in both of those things, but I'm devoted to prayer because I've come to believe that life to the full starts and ends with remaining in the love of God.

22:42.492 --> 22:43.794
And that's what prayer is.

22:45.058 --> 22:54.851
Both Matthew and Mark's Gospels show us that when Jesus returns from this mountaintop encounter, he is greeted by an absolute mess waiting on him in the village below.

22:55.512 --> 23:01.120
His disciples are trying to heal a boy of epilepsy and it's not going well to put it very politely.

23:01.981 --> 23:08.170
And so Jesus then heals and delivers this boy and then his disciples ask him, verse 19, why couldn't we drive it out?

23:08.851 --> 23:11.314
He replied, because you have so little faith.

23:11.522 --> 23:17.087
Truly, I tell you, if you have faith as small as a mustard seed, you can say to this mountain, move from here to there, and it will move.

23:17.147 --> 23:18.749
Nothing will be impossible for you.

23:20.230 --> 23:33.283
Both Henry, now, and Ann, Dallas, Willard argue that the Greek word, pistis, which is translated here and appears frequently in the Bible, translated as faith, is actually best translated, trust.

23:34.544 --> 23:40.530
Because faith is the active outward expression of an internal restored trust.

23:41.282 --> 23:45.750
The serpent in the garden didn't attack Eve's faith, making her doubt God's power.

23:46.672 --> 23:50.900
The serpent attacked Eve's trust, making her doubt God's love.

23:52.022 --> 23:55.789
And that's what makes mountaintop moments in our spiritual lives useful.

23:56.330 --> 24:02.962
They restored us a trust that the God that we heard on the mountaintop is the exact same in the valley.

24:03.522 --> 24:12.577
And so we put trust into action, believing ourselves to be his beloved and acting in step with that belief long after the inspiration is worn off.

24:13.117 --> 24:18.065
That's what Jesus means when he drops this famous mustard seed mountain moving line.

24:18.486 --> 24:28.402
He's saying something like, if you believe that I am who you met on the mountaintop and you are my beloved, you will be untouchable by the deceiver of this world.

24:28.898 --> 24:35.006
you will be able to effortlessly restore creation by heavenly power because you are rooted in a heavenly identity.

24:35.848 --> 24:47.784
Prayer is the practice of beholding Jesus a glow and listening to the Father's voice, but prayer is also an invitation to live with a tinge of that glow still on my face after I say amen.

24:48.585 --> 24:55.154
It's not to escape this world into a holy moment, but to glimpse my ordinary life.

24:55.906 --> 25:04.114
on the sidewalks of Brooklyn or the schoolyard in Portland as a glow with the burning potential of all of those holy moments.

25:04.635 --> 25:12.683
Will I trust that the God that I met in prayer is every bit as alive, interested, and involved after I say amen?

25:13.164 --> 25:17.008
That is the mustard seed-sized faith that restores all of creation.

25:18.069 --> 25:23.314
So prayer begins on Mount Tabor, but then it moves to the Mount of Olives.

25:24.226 --> 25:33.505
Matthew, Mark, and Luke all remember this peak as the side of Jesus' arrest when he was interrupted by Judas and a team of officers while praying in Gethsemane.

25:34.387 --> 25:38.375
Luke, though, points out this little tidbit, Luke 22, verse 39.

25:39.437 --> 25:45.970
Jesus went out as usual to the Mount of Olives, and his disciples followed him.

25:46.690 --> 26:01.077
This is a hint back to the previous chapter of Luke's gospel when he tells us that the whole of the week that we now call Holy Week, the final seven days of Jesus' life, he went to pray at the Mount of Olives every single night.

26:01.858 --> 26:05.204
So this is more than just the side of one famous prayer.

26:05.265 --> 26:08.210
This is a frequent favorite prayer spot of Jesus.

26:08.706 --> 26:21.617
Matthew, Mark, and Luke all remember the same prayer that Jesus prayed on this mountain when he fell to his knees and through blood and sweat prayed, Father, if you are willing, take this cup from me, yet not what I will, but your will be done.

26:22.419 --> 26:26.770
John's gospel, though, recalls a different prayer from the same mountain on the same night.

26:26.882 --> 26:31.828
One that Jesus prayed on his way to the garden where he fell on his knees.

26:31.868 --> 26:35.532
A prayer that is typically called the high priestly prayer.

26:35.912 --> 26:39.817
And it's among the most joyful prayers, prayed in all of scripture.

26:40.237 --> 26:41.078
So check this out.

26:42.060 --> 26:48.627
On the final night of Jesus' life, Jesus prayed both joyfully and sorrowfully.

26:49.708 --> 26:54.514
And both Jesus' joy and his sorrow are born from empathy.

26:55.106 --> 27:14.155
He is empathetically excited about what he's going to share with you and I, and he is empathetically dreading all that he's about to endure for you and I. Jesus' internal world, as revealed by his prayers, is unique in this way, that for Jesus, power hasn't eroded empathy.

27:15.537 --> 27:23.730
You see, the psychological consensus is that power in any form among any community at any stage of life

27:24.098 --> 27:25.179
is bad for you.

27:26.341 --> 27:30.867
If power was a prescription drug, it would come with a long list of side effects.

27:30.927 --> 27:32.309
Power can intoxicate.

27:32.710 --> 27:33.611
It can corrupt.

27:33.951 --> 27:34.852
It can distort.

27:35.193 --> 27:53.938
And that holds true whether we're talking about organizational power at a mid-level management, at a corporation, or the social power that you might hold, where you walk into a room where you're known and comfortable and others aren't, or being in the popular crowd at high school, or being in the in-group at work.

27:54.018 --> 28:05.521
And it holds for the spiritual power of being called pastor, or teacher, or community leader, or head of the serving team.

28:07.024 --> 28:14.258
Psychologist Dr. Keltner writes, once we have power, we lose some of the capacities we needed to get it in the first place.

28:14.786 --> 28:30.930
He names this the power paradox, and it's backed by more than 20 years of lab and field experiments, all of which verify that people with power behave psychologically speaking pretty much identically to people who have gone through a traumatic brain injury.

28:31.554 --> 28:40.708
They become more impulsive and less self-aware, less risk, averse, less adept at seeing their point of view through the eyes of another.

28:40.728 --> 28:54.209
His conclusion is that people in power actually gained that power through empathy, meaning you gain social influence by seeing and understanding on the other in a way that would engender their trust.

28:55.210 --> 28:57.554
And despite our best efforts,

28:57.762 --> 29:04.630
at creating responsible org charts and structured review processes, that's the main way you move up at work, too.

29:05.611 --> 29:08.094
Like, you gain the trust of the people that call the shots.

29:09.136 --> 29:13.701
And it's the way that you gain spiritual authority in the life of someone else.

29:14.442 --> 29:16.745
Empathy wins power.

29:17.866 --> 29:21.330
But, Keltner continues, power then leaks empathy.

29:21.794 --> 29:26.661
So the longer you have it, the less you have what got you that power in the first place.

29:27.142 --> 29:28.304
Isn't that fascinating?

29:29.606 --> 29:33.412
Empathy is the pathway to power and power is the Kryptonite of empathy.

29:35.254 --> 29:36.576
This blew my mind, right?

29:37.578 --> 29:48.274
So maybe the great power abuse scandals in recent history that have poured out of the corporate world and the political world and the church

29:48.898 --> 30:00.074
aren't the result of a few bad apples, but the result of power's corrosive effect on seeing another with dignity and love, empathy.

30:01.216 --> 30:03.980
This is one of the characteristics that makes Jesus so unique.

30:04.360 --> 30:09.187
He operates in an extraordinary amount of power through empathy.

30:10.048 --> 30:14.956
The power of the spirit that we see in Jesus doesn't erode empathy, it amplifies it.

30:15.717 --> 30:16.658
How did that happen?

30:16.994 --> 30:20.340
How did Jesus increase in power without decreasing in empathy?

30:22.163 --> 30:22.484
Prayer.

30:24.126 --> 30:27.492
Jesus was called both a glutton and a drunkard and a man of sorrows.

30:28.274 --> 30:33.122
Jesus was accused and critiqued of being too joyful and too sorrowful.

30:33.923 --> 30:39.974
And that's who prayer will make you, someone who holds both joy and sorrow authentically in tension.

30:41.256 --> 30:42.418
Henry Nowhan says,

30:42.562 --> 30:47.129
Prayer always leads us to the heart of God and the heart of the human struggle at the same time.

30:48.171 --> 30:56.563
So prayer is where empathy is cultivated because prayer is where we identify with both the victorious promises of God and the present pains of the world simultaneously.

30:57.465 --> 31:01.992
Prayer is the practice of joy and sorrow held together in tension in my one person.

31:02.412 --> 31:04.055
Prayer is the practice of empathy.

31:05.697 --> 31:11.506
Last spring, I spent a week teaching at a few different gatherings throughout the United Kingdom

31:11.586 --> 31:30.430
And I took my mom with me and it was really, really special because first she'd never been to England, but secondly and more so because it is the only week that I have ever spent alone with her in my life to date and probably the only one that I ever will.

31:31.210 --> 31:34.034
I've spent a ton of time with my mom

31:34.338 --> 31:36.441
But I'm also the middle child of three boys.

31:36.501 --> 31:39.866
And so growing up, I shared my mom with my dad and my brothers.

31:40.287 --> 31:43.411
And now I share her with my dad, my brothers, and nine grandkids.

31:43.952 --> 31:47.717
Every time we're together, we're surrounded by a sea of relatives.

31:48.338 --> 31:50.421
But here we were on a 10-hour flight.

31:50.481 --> 31:53.526
Just the two of us was seven days stretching out ahead of us.

31:54.447 --> 32:02.098
And while we were there, she got word that her very best friend from high school was in critical condition and had just days to live.

32:03.618 --> 32:08.651
And so right in front of me on that trip, separated by an ocean, she began to grieve.

32:10.015 --> 32:12.341
And she was getting frequent updates from her family.

32:12.422 --> 32:14.768
She was recalling memories of growing up together.

32:14.828 --> 32:17.074
She was carrying some very real sorrow.

32:18.562 --> 32:24.589
But she also wanted to remember this trip forever because it was so unique to treasure these few days that we had together.

32:24.609 --> 32:32.037
And so on our last day in a little English countryside town, she pulled me into a CD tattoo parlor.

32:32.398 --> 32:36.442
And we got matching tattoos to mark the moment.

32:36.462 --> 32:38.705
So I'm just sitting there and I'm looking at my mom.

32:38.765 --> 32:44.031
Here she is in her sixties getting inked up for the first time in her life.

32:44.271 --> 32:46.674
And I guarantee you,

32:47.170 --> 32:50.595
that in ten years that's the only thing either of us will remember about the trip.

32:53.219 --> 33:11.106
I'll forget what we ate for dinner and whether our flights were on time or delayed and how it went and each of the teachings that I offered, but my mom agonizing in pain and laughing hysterically as that little needle drew a leaf on her ankle, I will remember that forever.

33:11.727 --> 33:16.114
And so will she because she was sorrowful and grief.

33:16.802 --> 33:19.987
but alive in joy, both at the same time.

33:20.948 --> 33:25.795
Romans 12, 15 famously says, rejoice with those who rejoice, mourn with those who mourn.

33:26.456 --> 33:28.459
In other words, cultivate empathy, says Paul.

33:28.499 --> 33:31.704
That is a distinguishing marker of all of Jesus's apprentices.

33:32.365 --> 33:41.379
Love the idea, but it's also a lot easier said than done because every person who lives in this world accrues some degree of power.

33:42.220 --> 33:46.386
And power slowly, surely erodes the empathy that is required.

33:46.658 --> 33:48.981
to enter into the joy and sorrow of others.

33:49.322 --> 33:50.083
So how then?

33:50.503 --> 33:52.606
How do we empathize with our fellow human beings?

33:52.926 --> 33:58.974
How do we hold on to love so that we use every ounce of power we accumulate in service of love?

33:59.415 --> 34:01.057
Well, just zoom out a little bit.

34:01.097 --> 34:02.599
Paul already told us that part.

34:03.360 --> 34:06.484
Romans chapter 12, beginning three verses before.

34:07.065 --> 34:11.791
Be joyful and hope patient in affliction and devoted to prayer.

34:12.793 --> 34:13.874
Proskaterreo.

34:16.034 --> 34:24.088
Share with the Lord's people who are in need, practice hospitality, bless those who persecute you, bless and do not curse, rejoice with those who rejoice, mourn with those who mourn.

34:24.128 --> 34:42.258
Do you want to grow old into the sort of person who weeps empathetically with a friend decades old from across the world and the sort of person who on the very same day says, stick a needle into me, buddy, because this body of mine is going to expire, but this memory with my son never will.

34:42.370 --> 34:50.744
Do you want to grow old into someone who holds joy and sorrow together than devote yourself to prayer?

34:51.805 --> 35:02.162
Because it is the only thing that will make you more and not less as you go on devoted to it over the days of your life.

35:03.298 --> 35:13.376
And we tend to think or imagine that being devoted to prayer means that I'm going to grow more stoic and more religious and more serious about my life and my routines and my habits.

35:13.736 --> 35:28.242
But if we're taking our cues from Jesus, it seems to me that a life more devoted to prayer means being devout about one relationship so that I can become more joyful and sorrowful in all of my other relationships.

35:28.898 --> 35:36.487
Mount of all of prayers, the sort that open our eyes and wonder and drive us to our knees in agony.

35:36.867 --> 35:44.756
It seems to me that they work together to form us into the sort of people who can express spiritual power through empathy.

35:46.158 --> 35:49.862
A prayer shaped life is not a more stoic, more religious, or more serious life.

35:51.043 --> 35:53.426
It's not even necessarily a life

35:53.538 --> 35:58.425
of more time spent in prayer or more intense prayers that come out of me.

35:58.805 --> 36:03.151
It's more joy and sorrow in all the moments that I go on living after I say Amen.

36:03.732 --> 36:08.379
It is a life more full because of one solitary devotion.

36:09.941 --> 36:18.172
One more mountain, Golgotha, the mountain or the hill on which Jesus was crucified.

36:19.073 --> 36:22.418
Jesus' last word spoken from the cross, they were a prayer.

36:22.850 --> 36:28.237
A prayer that was not original to Jesus, but one that he borrowed from the Psalm, Psalm 22, verse one.

36:28.818 --> 36:31.682
My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?

36:32.763 --> 36:42.756
But this prayer of Jesus is really important for a multitude of reasons, but one of them is certainly just the honest realization that a prayer shaped life is a more painful life.

36:44.679 --> 36:48.484
To devote yourself to prayer is to welcome joy absolutely.

36:48.504 --> 36:50.066
It is fullness of life.

36:50.274 --> 36:53.940
But that fullness also includes sorrow of the most personal variety.

36:55.282 --> 37:10.945
If you devote yourself to prayer, you will live more fully, you will laugh harder, you will be more present, you will cherish the precious moments, you will press each one of your days like a grape under your laughing feet to strain out the intoxicating wine within it.

37:11.446 --> 37:19.538
And if you devote yourself to prayer, you will be confronted by more pain, by more disappointment,

37:20.866 --> 37:25.371
by more deafening silence, by more heart-rending disillusionment.

37:26.612 --> 37:30.857
In a God-empowered but serpent-deceived world, you do not get one without the other.

37:31.858 --> 37:46.994
If you want to ascend taper to see Jesus aglow and hear the Father's voice over you, if you want to ascend Gethsemane to grow old into a woman that gets tatted up in CD shops and English countryside with her son, well then you're going to have to march up Golgotha.

37:47.970 --> 37:54.096
to hang on your own cross next to Jesus, crying between tears, blood, and baited breath, my God, my God.

37:54.937 --> 37:56.399
Why have you forsaken me?

37:57.520 --> 38:01.304
Why have you forgotten me, left me alone, left me for dead?

38:03.586 --> 38:09.152
Joanie, a 17-year-old high school girl, went to the beach one summer in 1967.

38:09.212 --> 38:15.538
She enthusiastically dove into the water, not knowing how shallow it was in her head at the bottom.

38:16.066 --> 38:19.732
fracturing her spine between the fourth and fifth cervical level vertebrae.

38:20.734 --> 38:24.160
She has now lived more than 50 years, paralyzed from her neck down.

38:25.362 --> 38:30.952
And when she tells her own story, the first prayer, Joni says she prayed after her accident was why?

38:30.972 --> 38:38.706
In her own words, for the longest time I tried to twist God's arm so he'd reveal why I had my accident.

38:39.810 --> 38:46.959
And that prayer, some version of it, is the first kind of dialogue most people exchange with God when confronted by any variety of suffering.

38:48.041 --> 38:48.601
Why this?

38:48.661 --> 38:50.023
Why me?

38:50.063 --> 38:51.545
Why now?

38:51.565 --> 39:07.986
I called it dialogue, but the truth is it's more of a monologue because this type of prayer, these why prayers, both biblically and experientially, they are nearly always met with the silence of God, not a satisfying response.

39:09.314 --> 39:13.278
She then turned from asking God for an explanation to asking God for a miracle.

39:13.359 --> 39:16.462
She started confidently telling her friends, pray for my healing.

39:16.522 --> 39:19.185
Next time you see me, I'm going to be standing up out of this wheelchair.

39:21.247 --> 39:29.937
Three years into her suffering and God's seeming silence and no miracle, Joni was clinically depressed and she was battling suicidal ideation.

39:32.200 --> 39:37.746
Jesus prayed the first line of Psalm 22 in Jerusalem.

39:38.626 --> 39:40.814
before a majority Jewish crowd.

39:42.239 --> 39:44.968
Now the Psalms are the prayer book of the Jewish people.

39:45.008 --> 39:48.882
They committed most of the Psalms, if not all 150 Psalms.

39:48.930 --> 39:49.891
to memory.

39:50.191 --> 40:05.845
They recited these words in the temple each and every time they gathered to pray the first words of Psalm 22 before a Jewish crowd would have been like praying the first line of the Lord's Prayer in front of a Christian church or singing the first line of the Star Spangled Banner in front of a group of Americans.

40:05.965 --> 40:10.309
The whole psalm is implied in just uttering the first line.

40:10.629 --> 40:18.916
The whole ancient prayer would suddenly be downloaded into the imaginations of everyone who heard the first line of the ancient prayer and that

40:18.896 --> 40:24.827
matters because that prayer reads this way, my God, my God, why have you forsaken me?

40:24.867 --> 40:29.395
Why were you so far from saving me, so far from my cries of anguish?

40:29.736 --> 40:37.810
My God, I cry out by day, but you do not answer by night, but I find no rest, yet you are enthroned as the holy one.

40:38.786 --> 40:42.811
You are the one Israel praises and you are ancestors, put their trust.

40:42.851 --> 40:45.854
They trusted and you delivered them to you.

40:45.934 --> 40:51.660
They cried out and were saved and you they trusted and were not put to shame.

40:51.700 --> 40:56.286
It's a prayer that begins with the felt sense of God's absence, but it doesn't stay there.

40:57.867 --> 41:02.973
Here is the mystery unveiled in Jesus's final prayer, the mystery that is captured in Psalm 22.

41:03.934 --> 41:07.378
God's presence is experienced most profoundly.

41:07.970 --> 41:14.802
by praying through the pain of God's felt absence.

41:14.822 --> 41:20.251
It is a great grace to experience God's presence in our feelings and thoughts.

41:21.673 --> 41:27.123
But even when we don't, that doesn't mean that God is absent.

41:27.143 --> 41:33.714
But only those who keep on praying apart from the good feeling that prayer sometimes offers

41:34.114 --> 41:37.919
get to discover the rush of God's presence that comes to the waiting.

41:39.322 --> 41:39.622
C.S.

41:39.642 --> 41:45.771
Lewis wrote, I know now, Lord, why you utter no answer, you are yourself the answer.

41:46.672 --> 41:48.755
Before your face, questions die away.

41:48.815 --> 41:51.379
What other answer would suffice?

41:52.741 --> 42:01.874
Similarly Psalm 73 reads, when I tried to understand all this, it troubled me deeply till I entered the sanctuary of God.

42:02.850 --> 42:09.643
Joni, clinically depressed and battling suicidal ideation, prayed what she calls the most powerful prayer of her life.

42:10.385 --> 42:14.312
God, if I can't die, show me how to live, please.

42:14.352 --> 42:19.563
And later she would reflect he has chosen not to heal me but to hold me.

42:20.625 --> 42:23.410
The more intense the pain the closer his embrace.

42:24.642 --> 42:24.882
C.S.

42:25.083 --> 42:41.605
Lewis, Jr., and Tada and the biblical Psalms, they all seem to be naming the great mystery and the great grace of prayer that where God's absence is most painfully felt, His presence is most profoundly revealed, if we pray through our pain.

42:43.308 --> 42:46.011
And that's a whole lot more than just comforting theory.

42:46.051 --> 42:50.898
That is the story of countless friends that I've walked with closely and my own story.

42:51.874 --> 43:06.089
It's a story of friends that I've gotten to walk with through prolonged battles of infertility and countless miscarriages, through the loss of parents, siblings, friends, and children, through slowly debilitating diagnoses, and through immediately debilitating emergencies.

43:07.210 --> 43:19.122
The anthropologist, Tonya Lourman, who authored this fascinating book called How God Becomes Real, notes that Christian prayer among all spiritual practices seems to have significant psychological benefits.

43:19.746 --> 43:41.746
In fact, the psychological results from a non-praying person who begins to pray to Jesus are nearly identical to the psychological results of a new patient who begins CBT, cognitive behavioral therapy, which is among the most common and universally employed psychological techniques for revisiting, healing from, and overcoming trauma.

43:41.986 --> 43:54.665
When we experience the pain of God's absence, praying through that absence is a gateway to our healing, overcoming, and even deepening our sense of God's presence, even on a psychological level.

43:56.808 --> 44:03.698
In 2018, on top of her paralysis, Joni was in the midst of her second bout with stage three breast cancer.

44:04.802 --> 44:12.814
And she was dazed and nauseous in the passenger seat of her car sitting next to her husband, Ken, as he was driving her home from another day of chemotherapy.

44:13.576 --> 44:23.471
And as he looked at his wife reeling and broken next to him, he said to her, suffering is like splashovers of hell, isn't it?

44:23.491 --> 44:27.497
And then they rode the rest of the way home in silence.

44:27.517 --> 44:33.266
Until as they pulled into the driveway, Ken said, what do you think splashovers of heaven are?

44:34.274 --> 44:38.259
Are they those easy breezy times when everything's going your way when you have your health?

44:40.001 --> 44:41.463
Nah, Joni said.

44:42.825 --> 44:46.530
Splashovers of heaven are finding Jesus in your splashover of hell.

44:47.511 --> 44:51.757
And to find Jesus in your hell is ecstasy beyond compare.

44:53.639 --> 45:01.970
You see, the ultimate fruit for those who pray through God's absence isn't the comfort of God's temporary presence and our pain as good as that is, but the sure hope

45:02.210 --> 45:06.498
of God's constant presence without pain.

45:06.518 --> 45:13.492
Jesus' Golgoth, the prayer, was His final words for approximately 72 hours.

45:15.415 --> 45:18.481
But not His final words, because death for Jesus was not an end.

45:18.521 --> 45:19.423
It was a new beginning.

45:20.104 --> 45:23.571
And when Jesus was resurrected, He did not transcend His body.

45:24.232 --> 45:25.074
He redeemed it.

45:25.602 --> 45:37.597
scars are still on his skin telling the story of his victory and he invites his disciples to touch him and when they do their hand doesn't pass through a ghostly figure it runs into a flesh and blood skin and bone person.

45:38.338 --> 45:47.730
The resurrection of Jesus means that the soul doesn't transcend the body but that both the soul and the body will be healed fully and finally.

45:48.098 --> 45:57.627
And the return of Jesus means that one day soon, I will know God's constant presence in God's painless world without end, just like he always meant it to be.

45:57.988 --> 46:02.793
And that is a comforting and abstract thought until you pray through your own Golgotha.

46:04.114 --> 46:10.861
And on that day, when you do, if you do, it will become a sure and resilient foundation of hope.

46:12.582 --> 46:16.306
Joni still believes that she's gonna stand up and walk out of her wheelchair one day.

46:17.282 --> 46:27.838
What she's not sure about is when, whether it will be in this life or the next, but stand up and walk, she is sure that that is the future she's walking toward.

46:28.519 --> 46:29.761
And that is the real gift.

46:29.801 --> 46:40.377
That is the after amen fruit for those who pray through their pain, a sure hope that every last one of Jesus's promises is for real and for me.

46:41.839 --> 46:43.922
So all this, my friends,

